{"cursor":"13896","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" of the sequence, a number that it will forever approach but never touch:\n 2 , 3/2 , and 4/3 , respectively.]] In\n mathematics, a 'geometric progression', also known as a 'geometric sequence',\n is a sequence of numbers where each term after the first is found by\n multiplying the previous one by a fixed, non-zero number called the common\n ratio. For example, the sequence 2, 6, 18, 54, ... is a geometric progression\n with common ratio 3. Similarly 10, 5, 2.5, 1.25, ... is a geometric sequence\n with common ratio 1/2. The sum of the terms of a geometric progression, or of\n an initial segment of a geometric progression, is known as a geometric series.\n\nThus, the general form of a geometric sequence is\n\n: a,\\ ar,\\ ar^2,\\ ar^3,\\ ar^4,\\ \\ldots\n\nand that of a geometric series is\n\n: a + ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + ar^4 + \\cdots\n\nwhere r â  0 is the common ratio and a is a scale factor, equal to the sequence's\nstart value.\n","linknr":267,"url":"Geometric_progression","recorded":1362372658,"links":60,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Sequences and series","Mathematical series","Articles containing proofs"],"headings":["Elementary properties","Geometric series","Product","Relationship to geometry and Euclid's work","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Geometric_sequences.svg/300px-Geometric_sequences.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/8/1/c81e728d9d4c2f636f067f89cc14862c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/0/f/00fd1da21e8b4ef31d987665dc575099.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/7/0/87069d0b9cbfd259ce8e4a8198f527fe.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/5/b/15b1e5bc8f8e8c5e7d46fd177eb625d6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/8/d/e8d3eb469951c8d01627845afb636c4c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/e/3/6e3a